06578nam a22011055i 9780691214290DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20201996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912142907 a10.1515/97806912142902doi  a(DE-B1597)554779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBR166b.S75 1996 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a306.67012211 aStark, Rodney, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rise of Christianity :bA Sociologist Reconsiders History /cRodney Stark. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b10 b/w illus. 10 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tCHAPTER 1 Conversion and Christian Growth -- tCHAPTER 2 The Class Basis of Early Christianity -- tCHAPTER 3 The Mission to the Jews: Why It Probably Succeeded -- tCHAPTER 4 Epidemics, Networks, and Conversion -- tCHAPTER 5 The Role of Women in Christian Growth -- tCHAPTER 6 Christianizing the Urban Empire: A Quantitative Approach -- tCHAPTER 7 Urban Chaos and Crisis: The Case of Antioch -- tCHAPTER 8 The Martyrs: Sacrifice as Rational Choice -- tCHAPTER 9 Opportunity and Organization -- tCHAPTER 10 A Brief Reflection on Virtue -- tNotes -- tBibliograph -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe idea that Christianity started as a clandestine movement among the poor is a widely accepted notion. Yet it is one of many myths that must be discarded if we are to understand just how a tiny messianic movement on the edge of the Roman Empire became the dominant faith of Western civilization. In a fast-paced, highly readable book that addresses beliefs as well as historical facts, Rodney Stark brings a sociologist's perspective to bear on the puzzle behind the success of early Christianity. He comes equipped not only with the logic and methods of social science but also with insights gathered firsthand into why people convert and how new religious groups recruit members. He digs deep into the historical evidence on many issues--such as the social background of converts, the mission to the Jews, the status of women in the church, the role of martyrdom--to provide a vivid and unconventional account of early Christianity. The author plots the most plausible curve of Christian growth from the year 40 to 300. By the time of Constantine, Christianity had become a considerable force, with growth patterns very similar to those of modern-day successful religious movements. An unusual number of Christian converts, for example, came from the educated, cosmopolitan classes. Because it offered a new perspective on familiar concepts and was not linked to ethnicity, Christianity had a large following among persons seeking to assimilate into the dominant culture, mainly Hellenized Jews. The oversupply of women in Christian communities--due partly to the respect and protection they received--led to intermarriages with pagans, hence more conversions, and to a high fertility rate. Stark points out, too, the role played by selflessness and faith. Amidst the epidemics, fires, and other disasters that beleaguered Greco-Roman cities, Christian communities were a stronghold of mutual aid, which resulted in a survival rate far greater than that of the pagans. In the meantime, voluntary martyrdom, especially a generation after the death of Christ, reinforced the commitment of the Christian rank and file. What Stark ultimately offers is a multifaceted portrait of early Christianity, one that appeals to practical reasoning, historical curiosity, and personal reflection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aChristian sociologyxHistoryyEarly church, 